    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-01T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-01T12:00:00-05:00" n="998"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d998">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.6354/121: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-01T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 1, 1939—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 1—3:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>586. The Embassy suggested to Todd that he call upon the Minister at The Hague
                    after the recent meeting of the International Tin Regulation <pb facs="0934"
                        n="922" xml:id="pg_922"/> Committee in that city. Todd has now returned to
                    London and states that he did so and gave the Minister an account of the
                    Committee’s deliberations including the statements by the manager of the buffer
                    stock pool (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) that it now held 13,000 tons and (<hi
                        rend="italic">b</hi>) that he intended to begin selling as soon as the price
                    reached the level of £226–£227. After the meeting, Mills<note n="80"
                        xml:id="d998fn80">Buffer pool operator.</note> told Todd in reply to the
                    latter’s criticism of the high price level at which the stocks operations would
                    begin, that he hoped in due course to work the price down.</p>
                <p>Todd assumes that the Iron and Steel Federation will continue to pass on to the
                    Department copies of his telegraphic and written reports. He has suggested that
                    American buyers switch their purchases from Straits tin, which normally sells at
                    a premium of about £7, to standard tin until the price moves down. From a
                    tactical point of view this suggestion has merit in view of the fact that Malaya
                    is the highest grade and cheapest cost producer and that there was an important
                    section of Malayan tin interests which were even opposed to the formation of the
                    buffer stock pool. Since the United States is the largest consumer of Straits
                    tin Malaya would make its voice heard on the buffer stock policy.</p>
                <p>Incidentally at Campbell’s request all the discussion on the buffer stock was
                    omitted from the official minutes of the meeting.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
